Project Business Statistics: E-news Express¶

Marks: 60

Define Problem Statement and Objectives¶

Problem Statement¶

The advent of e-news, or electronic news, portals has offered us a great opportunity to quickly get updates on the day-to-day events occurring globally. The information on these portals is retrieved electronically from online databases, processed using a variety of software, and then transmitted to the users. There are multiple advantages of transmitting new electronically, like faster access to the content and the ability to utilize different technologies such as audio, graphics, video, and other interactive elements that are either not being used or arent common yet in traditional newspapers.

E-news Express, an online news portal, aims to expand its business by acquiring new subscribers. With every visitor to the website taking certain actions based on their interest, the company plans to analyze these actions to understand user interests and determine how to drive better engagement. The executives at E-news Express are of the opinion that there has been a decline in new monthly subscribers compared to the past year because the current webpage is not designed well enough in terms of the outline & recommended content to keep customers engaged long enough to make a decision to subscribe.

[Companies often analyze user responses to two variants of a product to decide which of the two variants is more effective. This experimental technique, known as A/B testing, is used to determine whether a new feature attracts users based on a chosen metric.]

Objective¶

The design team of the company has researched and created a new landing page that has a new outline & more relevant content shown compared to the old page. In order to test the effectiveness of the new landing page in gathering new subscribers, the Data Science team conducted an experiment by randomly selecting 100 users and dividing them equally into two groups. The existing landing page was served to the first group (control group) and the new landing page to the second group (treatment group). Data regarding the interaction of users in both groups with the two versions of the landing page was collected. Being a data scientist in E-news Express, you have been asked to explore the data and perform a statistical analysis (at a significance level of 5%) to determine the effectiveness of the new landing page in gathering new subscribers for the news portal by answering the following questions:

  1. Do the users spend more time on the new landing page than on the existing landing page?

  2. Is the conversion rate (the proportion of users who visit the landing page and get converted) for the new page greater than the conversion rate for the old page?

  3. Does the converted status depend on the preferred language?

  4. Is the time spent on the new page the same for the different language users?

Data Dictionary¶

The data contains information regarding the interaction of users in both groups with the two versions of the landing page.

user_id - Unique user ID of the person visiting the website

group - Whether the user belongs to the first group (control) or the second group (treatment)

landing_page - Whether the landing page is new or old

time_spent_on_the_page - Time (in minutes) spent by the user on the landing page

converted - Whether the user gets converted to a subscriber of the news portal or not

language_preferred - Language chosen by the user to view the landing page

1. Do the users spend more time on the new landing page than the existing landing page?¶

Perform Visual Analysis¶

In [ ]:
# visual analysis of the time spent on the new page and the time spent on the old page
plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
sns.boxplot(x = 'landing_page', y = 'time_spent_on_the_page', data = df)
# Adjust the scale on setting the y-axis limits to [0, 12]
plt.ylim(0, 14)
plt.show()

Insight

  • The time spent on both old and new landing page is just about normally distributed, with few outliers in the new landing page.

  • Median time spent on the new landing page was more than the median time spent on the old landing page.

  • The range of time spent on the old landing page was significantly wider when compared to the range of time spent on the new landing page.

  • This may point to a signifcant improvement in time spent on the new landing page when compared to the old landing page. This observation will be further tested in this section.

Step 1: Define the null and alternate hypotheses¶

The null and alternative hypotheses is formulated as:

H0 : The time spent by users in new landing page is less or equal to the time spent on the existing landing page

Ha : The time spent by users in new landing page is more than the time spent on the existing landing page

Step 2: Select Appropriate test¶

This problem is concerning two independent populations,the group who use the existing landing and the group that use the new landing page. The variable here is time spent on the landing pages when they visit. The population standard deviation is also not known. Hence, One-tailed two sample independent T-test is the appropriate test for this problem.

Let's test whether the T-test assumptions are satisfied or not Continuous data - Yes, the usage time is measured on a continuous scale.

  1. Normally distributed populations - Yes, we can assume these based on the boxplot we viewed earlier.

  2. Independent populations - As we are taking random samples for two different type of users, the two samples are from two independent populations.

  3. Random sampling from the population - Yes, we are informed that the collected sample is a simple random sample.

Step 3: Decide the significance level¶

The significant level used will be $\alpha = 0.05$

Step 4: Collect and prepare data¶

In [ ]:
# create separate variables to store the time spent on the page with respect to the two landing pages
Existing_landing_page = df[df['landing_page']=='old']['time_spent_on_the_page']
New_landing_page = df[df['landing_page']=='new']['time_spent_on_the_page']
In [ ]:
# Calculating the mean and standard deviations of time spent on each landing page
print('Standard deviation of time spent on existing landing page is',round(np.std(Existing_landing_page),2))
print('Standard deviation of time spent on new landing page is', round(np.std(New_landing_page),2))
print('mean time spent on existing landing page is', round(np.mean(Existing_landing_page),2))
print('mean time spent on new landing page is', round(np.mean(New_landing_page),2))

Standard deviation of time spent on existing landing page is 2.56
Standard deviation of time spent on new landing page is 1.8
mean time spent on existing landing page is 4.53
mean time spent on new landing page is 6.22

Step 5: Calculate the p-value¶

The ttest_ind() function of Scipy will be used to compute the test statistic and p-value. Since variance is not the same in both population, the parameter equal_var will equal false.

In [ ]:
#import the required functions
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind

# find the p-value
test_stat, p_value = ttest_ind(New_landing_page.dropna(),Existing_landing_page.dropna(), equal_var = False, alternative = 'greater')
print('The p-value is ', p_value)

The p-value is  0.0001392381225166549

Step 6: Compare the p-value with $\alpha$¶

In [ ]:
# print the conclusion based on p-value
if p_value < 0.05:
    print(f'As the p-value {p_value} is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.')
else:
    print(f'As the p-value {p_value} is greater than the level of significance, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.')

As the p-value 0.0001392381225166549 is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.

Step 7: Draw inference¶

With the P-value less than the level of significance, there is enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis and this implies that time spent on the new landing page by users is more than those spent on the old landing page.

2. Is the conversion rate (the proportion of users who visit the landing page and get converted) for the new page greater than the conversion rate for the old page?¶

Perform visual analysis¶

In [ ]:
# Plotting a barchart for Conversion proportion in each landing page
bar_group = sns.countplot(data=df, x='landing_page', hue ='converted')
plt.xlabel('Landing page')
plt.ylabel('count')
plt.title('Proportion of Users converted from each landing page')

# Adjust the scale on setting the y-axis limits to [0, 12]
plt.ylim(0, 50);

From the above visuals, we can see that the new landing page has more proportion of users converted when compared to the older landing page which had more proportion of users not converted. This will be further tested through hypothesis testing.

Define the null and alternate hypothesis¶

The null and alternative hypotheses is formulated as:

H0 : The conversion rate of the new llanding page is less than or equal to the conversion rate of the old landing page

Ha : The conversion rate of the new landing page is greater than that of the old landing page

Select appropriate test¶

The question seeks to know the proportion of converted(discrete variable) in a population(new landing page) as compared to same converted(discrete varible)in another population(old landing page). The ideal test for this question is a One-tailed 2-sample Z-test.

Let's test whether the Z-test assumptions are satisfied or not

  • Binomally distributed population - Yes, user is converted or not in each landing page population
  • Random sampling from the population - Yes, we are informed that the collected sample is a simple random sample.
  • Can the binomial distribution be approximated to normal distribution - Yes. For binary data, CLT works slower than usual. The standard thing is to check whether np and n(1-p) are greater than or equal to 10. Here, n and p refer to the sample size and sample proportion respectively.

np_1 > 10

n(1-p_1) > 10

np_2 > 10

n(1-p_2) > 10

These were all checked below, and found meeting the conditions for 2 sample z-test to be used.

In [ ]:
#getting the proportion of conversions in  landing page
n_old= len(df[(df['landing_page'] == 'old') & (df['converted'] == 'yes')])
p_old= len(df[df['landing_page']=='old'])
n_prop_old= n_old/p_old

#Checking if the conversion rate and sample size of the existing page is greater than 10
np_old1= p_old*(n_prop_old) # check sample size
np_old2= p_old*(p_old-n_old/p_old) #checking proportion size

#getting the proportion of conversions in the new  anding page
n_new= len(df[(df['landing_page'] == 'new') & (df['converted'] == 'yes')])
p_new= len(df[df['landing_page']=='new'])
n_prop_new= n_new/p_new
np_new1= p_new*(n_prop_new)

#Checking if the conversion rate and sample size of the new page is greater than 10
np_new1= p_new*(n_prop_new) #checking sample size
np_new2= p_old*p_new-n_new/p_new #checking proportion size

print('The np and n(1-p) for both proportions are',np_old1,'&',np_new1,'respectively and',np_old2,'&',np_new2,'respectively','which are all greater than 10 thus meeting the criteria that both binomial distributions can be approximated to normal distributions')

The np and n(1-p) for both proportions are 21.0 & 33.0 respectively and 2479.0 & 2499.34 respectively which are all greater than 10 thus meeting the criteria that both binomial distributions can be approximated to normal distributions

It is clear that both sample size(n) and sample proportion(p) for conversion rate in both existing and new landing page are above 10. Hence, the two sample z-test can be applied.

Decide significance level¶

The significant level used will be $\alpha = 0.05$

Collect and prepare data¶

In [ ]:
# Count of conversions in both landing pages
n_old= len(df[(df['landing_page'] == 'old') & (df['converted'] == 'yes')])  #conversions in existing landing page
n_new= len(df[(df['landing_page'] == 'new') & (df['converted'] == 'yes')])  #conversions in new landing page

#Sample sizes of both landing pages
p_old= len(df[df['landing_page']=='old'])  #existing page sample size
p_new= len(df[df['landing_page']=='new'])  #new page sample size

Calculate P-value¶

In [ ]:
# import the required fuction
from statsmodels.stats.proportion import proportions_ztest

# set the count of conversions in both landing pages
conversion_count = np.array([n_old, n_new])

# set the sample sizes of both landing pages
nobs = np.array([p_old, p_new])

# find the p-value
test_stat, p_value = proportions_ztest(conversion_count, nobs)
print('The p-value is ' + str(p_value))

The p-value is 0.016052616408112556

Compare the p-value with $\alpha$¶

In [ ]:
# print the conclusion based on p-value as compared with earlier stated level of significance.
if p_value < 0.05:
    print(f'As the p-value {p_value} is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.')
else:
    print(f'As the p-value {p_value} is greater than the level of significance, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.')

As the p-value 0.016052616408112556 is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.

Draw Inference¶

With the null hypothesis rejected, I can say that there is enough evidence to support the alternate theory that the conversion rate on the new landing page is greater than the conversion rate on the older landing page

Define Null and alternate hypothesis¶

The null and alternative hypotheses is formulated as:

H0 : Conversion is independent of the user preferred language

Ha : Conversion is related to the user preferred language.

Select appropriate test¶

The Chi Square test of independence is the appropriate test for this problem, as the below criteria has been met to use the test.

  1. Categorical variables - Yes,becuase Conversion and user_preferred language columns contain only categorical variables.
  2. Expected value of the number of sample observations in each level of the variable is at least 5 - Yes, the number of observations in each level is greater than 5.This will be further highlighted when the contigency table is visualized in the next section. 3.Random sampling from the population - Yes, we are informed that the collected sample is a simple random sample.

Decide level of significance¶

The significant level used will be $\alpha = 0.05$

Since the null hypothesis has failed to be rejected. I can say that there is not enough evidence to support the claim that there is a relationship between conversion and User language preferences eventhough exploratory analysis seem to back a relationship been present.

4. Is the time spent on the new page same for the different language users?¶

Insight

  • From the chart we can see that the difference in time spent on a landing page by the preferred language groups can only be described as marginal with only with a variaation around 2 minutes.

  • This may point to other factors driving time spent on the landing page rather than the language preference of the users. This observation will be tested below.

Define Null and alternate hypothesis.¶

The null and alternative hypotheses is formulated as:

H0 : Time spent on the new landing page is different for the different language users

Ha : Time spent on the new landing page is same for the different language users

Select appropriate test.¶

There are 3 populations to be tested for equality agaainst a variable.The populations are the Spanish,Enlish, and French users who used the new landing page, while the variable they are tested against is the time spent on the new landing page. The appropriate test for this problem is the One-way ANOVA F-test.

However,the normality of distribution and and equality of variance of the variable has to be check ascertain the accuracy of the test in solving the problem.

The Shapiro- Wilks test of normality and Levine test of variance equality will be used in checking its accuracy.

Shapiro-Wilks test We will test the null hypothesis

H0: Time spent on the new landing page follows a normal distribution

against the alternative hypothesis

Ha: Time spent on the new landing page does not follow a normal distribution.

WHILE

Levenes test We will test the null hypothesis

H0 : All the 3 population variances with regards time spent on landing page variances are equal

against the alternative hypothesis

Ha : At least one variance is different from the rest.

level of significance for both tests will be 0.05

Shapiro-Wilk's test¶

The shapiro() function of Scipy will be used to compute the test statistic and p-value of the Shapiro-Wilk's test.

In [ ]:
# Assumption 1: Normality
# Import the required function
from scipy.stats import shapiro

# Subset the DataFrame for the 'new' landing page
subset_data = df[df['landing_page'] == 'new']['time_spent_on_the_page']

# Perform the Shapiro-Wilk test
w, p_value = shapiro(subset_data)

# Output the p-value
print('The p-value is', p_value)

The p-value is 0.8040016293525696

Since p-value of the test is larger than o.o5, we fail to reject the null hypothesis,thus the time spent on the new page follows a normal distribution.

Levene's Test¶

The [levene()]function of Scipy will be used to compute the test statistic and p-value.

In [ ]:
df['language_preferred'].unique() #Checking unique values of preferred languages
Out[ ]:
array(['Spanish', 'English', 'French'], dtype=object)
In [26]:
#Assumption 2: Homogeneity of Variance
#import the required function
from scipy.stats import levene

# Subset the DataFrame for the 'new' landing page
subset_data_english = df[(df['landing_page'] == 'new') & (df['language_preferred'] == 'English')]['time_spent_on_the_page']
subset_data_spanish = df[(df['landing_page'] == 'new') & (df['language_preferred'] == 'Spanish')]['time_spent_on_the_page']
subset_data_french = df[(df['landing_page'] == 'new') & (df['language_preferred'] == 'French')]['time_spent_on_the_page']

statistic, p_value = levene(subset_data_english,subset_data_spanish,subset_data_french)
# find the p-value
print('The p-value is', p_value)

The p-value is 0.46711357711340173

Since the p-value is larger than 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis of homogeneity of variances.

Let's test whether the assumptions are satisfied or not¶

  • The populations are normally distributed - Yes, the normality assumption is verified using the Shapiro-Wilks test.
  • Samples are independent simple random samples - Yes, we are informed that the collected sample is a simple random sample.
  • Population variances are equal - Yes, the homogeneity of variance assumption is verified using the Levene's test.

Decide level of significance.¶

The significant level used will be $\alpha = 0.05$

Collect data and prepare data¶

Data need to be sorted to meet the criteria of the target population against variable.

Conclusion and Business Recommendations¶

Conclusion¶

  1. It has been proven that there is a significant improvement in time spent on the new landing page when compared to the old landing page. This may be as a result of the the new landing page being more user friendly, intusive, or containing more relevant content that is more accessible and appealing to users when compared to the old landing page.

  2. There is enough evidence to show that the conversion rate on the new page is significantly higher than those on the older page. This may be connected to the fact that when users spend more time on the landing page, there may be contents atrractive enough and intusive enough to want to explore the website deeper and thus get converted. This further backs the burden of evidence of users spending more time on the new landing page than the older one.

  3. There is no relationship between users converted and their preferred language. Rather, other factors on the landing page that engage the user more tend to make them convert.

  4. There are marginal differences in time spent on the new landing page across the 3 different preferred language groups, with English laguage users marginally spending the most time and French language preferred users marginally spending the least time. This may imply that are still more optimization needed on the French version of the new landing page to make users spend more time on that version of the landing page.

Business Recommendations¶

  1. The new landing page should be fully adopted as there is significant evidence to show it is superior to the older landing page.

  2. Eventhough the new landing page is far superior to the old landing page, more optimization is needed to increase conversion rate as well as time spent on the landing page.

  3. The new landing page version for French and Spanish preffered users require more optimization so it can be at par with the English version of the new landing page in terms of time spent on the landing page.
